### The Compelling Argument for Multiple-Asset-Class Investing

- **Table 8-1 provides perhaps the most compelling argument for multiple-asset-class investing**
- As we move toward broader diversification, rates of return increase, volatility levels decrease, and Sharpe ratios improve

#### The Four-Asset-Class Portfolio Advantage

- **The four-asset-class portfolio has a compound rate of return 1.2 percentage points higher than the average component return of its components**
- That is, **a $1 investment in a continuously rebalanced portfolio of all four components has a future value of $32.89** compared with an average future value of **$25.18** for the four components standing alone
- **The four-asset-class portfolio has 47 percent less volatility than the average volatility levels of its components**

#### Sharpe Ratio Comparison

- **The Sharpe ratio of the four-asset-class portfolio shows that it has generated nearly twice as much volatility-adjusted return as the average of its components**

### The Difficulty of Seeing Diversification Benefits

- It is often difficult to see the beneficial impact on return created by broader diversification because diversification examples mix fixed-income investments with equity investments
- In this situation, **the large difference between the returns of fixed-income and those of equity investments obscures the incremental portfolio return attributable to the diversification effect**
- Although one would expect that asset classes with similar volatility levels would have similar long-term return paths, **we are pedagogically fortunate to have the four equity asset class returns in our analysis be as close as they are**
- **As a result, you can see the positive impact diversification has on both reducing volatility and increasing return**

### The Sharpe Ratio Explained

> **Footnote 2**: The Sharpe ratio is a measure of reward relative to volatility. A portfolio's Sharpe ratio can be calculated easily using a simple spreadsheet program. The portfolio's returns are listed in one column, and those for Treasury bills are listed in the next column. The differences between the portfolio returns and Treasury bill returns are computed in the third column. The Sharpe ratio is equal to the average of the differences in column 3 divided by the standard deviation of these differences. **The Sharpe ratio affirms the notion that a portfolio should generate some incremental reward for the assumption of volatility; otherwise, it would be better to simply own Treasury bills.**

### 1998 Update: The Year That Made a Difference

- The author originally did this research toward the end of 1998
- As a result, **1997 was the last calendar year of data included in the analysis**
- **The year 1972 was chosen as the beginning point** because 1972 was the earliest year for which data were available for all four equity asset classes

#### The Dramatic 1998 Returns

- As fate would have it, 1998 was a year when there were **strikingly different returns across the four asset classes**, as shown in **Table 8-2**:
  - **S&P 500**: 28.58%
  - **EAFE**: 20.33%
  - **NAREIT**: -17.50%
  - **GSCI**: -35.75% (the biggest drop in commodity prices in over a century)

- As expected, **the marked disparity in 1998 returns triggered some significant repositioning of the 15 equity portfolios in volatility/return space**, as shown in **Figure 8-5**

### "End Point Sensitivity" and Its Implications

- **Figure 8-5 is a wonderful illustration of "end point sensitivity"**
- As a result of one additional year of data, **REITs fell from first to third place in return among the four asset classes** while the S&P 500 moved into first place
- Among the 15 equity portfolios, **the S&P 500 moved from thirteenth place to fifth place in compound annual return to second!**
- **This underscores the danger of naively extrapolating an asset class's relative performance into the future**

#### The Goldman Sachs Commodity Index Near-Catastrophe

- **The performance of the GSCI was so bad that the vertical axis in Figure 8-5 had to be rescaled; otherwise, it would have fallen off the graph**
- **The inclusion of 1998's returns flattened somewhat the pattern of portfolios in volatility/return space**
- Despite this repositioning, **the basic conclusion of the analysis remains the same**

