## Chapter 13: Resolving Problems Encountered During Implementation

### Opening Quote

> "There is nothing more profitable for a man than to take good counsel with himself; for even if the event turns out contrary to one's hope, still one's decision was right, even though fortune has made it of no effect: whereas if a man acts contrary to good counsel, although by luck he gets what he had no right to expect, his decision was not any the less foolish."

**—Herodotus (c. 485-425 B.C.), Histories**

## Client Inertia

### The Psychology of Selling Familiar Investments

- **Recommendations to sell old familiar investments** in order to buy new unfamiliar investments can generate client anxiety
- Even though changes may **substantially improve risk/return characteristics** of portfolio
- Complicated by fact that **clients tend to psychologically equate familiarity and comfort with safety**
- Can result in **inertia**
- Although recommended target portfolio looks good, **it is difficult for client to begin implementing the strategy**

### Advisor-Client Dialogue on Concentrated Position

More than once advisor has had following conversation with client:

**Advisor:** "You have very large percentage of your total portfolio committed to XYZ stock."

**Client:** "Yes, it has really done well. I bought it a few years ago for $10 per share, and now it is worth $85 per share."

**Advisor:** "That is great performance, but I'm concerned about the diversifiable volatility you retain by continuing to hold such a large position. The marketplace does not provide any compensation for volatility that can be eliminated through broad diversification."

**Client:** "Yes, but I really like XYZ stock."

**Advisor:** "The target portfolio we have designed can accommodate a position in the stock if you prefer, but we recommend that you substantially reduce the commitment. We have considered the tax implications of our recommendation and suggest that at least one third of your position be sold this year, with another one third sold next year. The remainder can be retained."

**Client:** "I understand what you are saying, but why should I get off a winning horse?"

**Advisor:** "Assume for a moment that you do not own the stock but have a sum of cash equal in value to your current stock commitment. Would you buy that much XYZ stock at today's price of $85 per share?"

**Client:** "No. I would never purchase a position that big if I had to buy it at today's price!"

**The conversation is followed by long pause while client ponders his response**

###解決 Client Inertia: The Psychological Barrier

**There is a tendency for clients to view appreciated assets as bargains**

- Because they think of them in terms of **low purchase prices**
- Of course, **historical cost has nothing to do** with whether stock will continue to perform well from its current market value of $85 per share
- By being asked whether he would purchase stock today if he did not already own it, client will be **liberated from his preoccupation with his low historical cost**
- Sometimes sufficient to resolve issue in favor of reducing commitment

**If inappropriately high position in stock is retained**, client should understand that he is **assuming diversifiable volatility for which there is no expected compensation**

### Tax Issues with Appreciated Investments

**Tax complications often complicate decision**, however

- Unless client expects to hold appreciated investment until he or she dies, **income taxes due on gain will have to be paid sooner or later**
- Although if true that taxes will not be paid until investment is sold, **government's claim on its share of appreciation nevertheless exists**
- For this reason, may be advisable to **carry this investment on client's balance sheet at lower value that adjusts for anticipated taxes** due upon sale

**This accomplishes two things:**

1. **Generates front awareness** that the investment should not be retained merely because its sale will trigger payment of income taxes
2. **Avoids perception of a decrease in net worth** as result of sale

### Income Yield Complications with Appreciated Assets

Another complicating factor when appreciated asset has **good income yield**

- Although government has claim on unrealized appreciation, **client nevertheless gets entire income stream** from investment

**Example of income yield consideration:**

- Consider stock with **$10 per share cost basis**, currently selling for $85 per share
- If it pays **$3.60 per year in dividends**, its **current income yield is 6 percent**
- Assume upon sale, **30 percent of realized gain will be lost to capital gains taxes**
- This leaves **after-tax sale proceeds of $45** available for repositioning
- In order to generate same $3.60 per share in income, need to find stock with **8 percent yield** ($45 × .08 = $3.60)
- This needs to be **carefully weighed** in retention/disposition decision

### Age, Health, and Stepped-Up Tax Basis

**Client's age and health also need to be considered** when evaluating disposition of appreciated asset

- Our current income tax code provides for **"stepped-up tax basis"** for appreciated assets upon investor's death
- If investor in above example was **terminally ill**, retention of this stock would probably be advisable
- Upon his death, **survivors would inherit stock with tax basis stepped up to current market value**
- This sidesteps the **$15 per share that would otherwise be lost to income taxes** had investor sold stock prior to his death

### Selling Investments with Unrealized Capital Losses

Sometimes advisor recommends that **investment be sold that has unusually large unrealized capital loss**

**Advisor-client conversation example:**

**Advisor:** "We recommend that your position in ABC Company be liquidated because it is not a preferred investment for the recommended target portfolio we designed together."

**Client:** "Yes, that stock has been rotten. I bought it for $50 per share, and now it's worth only $8 per share. But if I sell it now, I'll lose money." (Note subtle implication that if it is not sold, no money is lost!)

**Advisor:** "You have already lost the money."

**Client:** "No, I haven't. It's just a paper loss." (The comment presumes paper losses have no economic significance.)

**Advisor:** "Assume for a moment that you do not own the stock but have a sum of cash equal to your current commitment. Would you buy it today at $8 per share?"

**Client:** "No way. I can't wait to sell it, and as soon as it gets back to $50 per share, I'm dumping it!"

### The "Paper Loss Syndrome"

**Psychology underlying "paper loss syndrome":**

- Conviction that **no money is lost unless position is sold**
- **Paper losses have no economic substance**
- Again, apart from tax considerations, **historical cost should have nothing to do with retention/sale decision**
- What client is really resisting is **admission of having made an investment that did not work out well**
- **Once it is sold for a loss, the verdict is unavoidably apparent**
- But if investment is held, **there is still hope that some day the investment will break even**

### Overcoming Paper Loss Syndrome

**These problems can often be overcome by recommended exercise:**

- Having client **hypothetically assume that his/her entire portfolio has been converted to cash** before designing new target portfolio
- This **frees client from past decisions**
- Result: **new recommendations are no longer pitted against sale** of old and unfamiliar positions
- **Entire range of investment options**, including those positions client currently owns, are available for consideration as building blocks for target portfolio
- With this approach, **client may still decide to have some of old familiar investments retained**, but likelihood is that chosen percentage allocation for these investments will be more reasonable

### Active Investment Decision-Making

**Investment decisions should be active**

- Traditionally, investment recommendations have been classified as **buy, hold, or sell**
- Author thinks **"hold" recommendations** often evade responsibility for making active decisions and that **sell rule and buy rule should be one and the same**

**The fundamental rule stated simply:**

> "Hold in your portfolio only those investments that you would actively repurchase if you did not already own them. Sell everything else."

## Big Dollar Decisions

**Investing large sums of money is anxiety-producing situation** for many clients

- Particularly true for **unsophisticated clients** who may have suddenly won lottery or received large inheritance
- For first time in their lives they may be facing need to make **major investment decisions**

**Encouraging client to think holistically** regarding entire portfolio and **expressing investment recommendations as percentage of total portfolio** can alleviate part of anxiety

**Example:**

- Recommendation to invest **3 percent of $1 million portfolio** in commodity-linked securities sounds much less dramatic than investing **$30,000 in same position**

## Resistance to Specific Investment Recommendations

**It is client's money**, and it is appropriate that client have **veto power over any investment recommendation**

- Occasionally, however, client rejects specific investment **for wrong reasons**

**Example:**

- Client may reject recommended position in international stock mutual fund
- As you dig deeper, it becomes apparent that she is **not objecting to specific investment recommendation**
- Rather, she is **uncomfortable with international stocks as an asset class**
- When this occurs, it indicates that **prior, more general level of decision making was not firmed up properly** before proceeding to next step

### Portfolio Design Should Proceed Hierarchically

**The portfolio design process should proceed from broad portfolio balance level** to more delineated asset allocation level and then finally to **specific investment position level**

- **Each level of decision making should be firmly established** before proceeding to next
- If done properly, this will **generate positive momentum** in decision-making process and **avoid messy situation** where client objects to specific investment for reasons that should have been addressed at more general level of decision making

**Resolution process:**

- If it is fine for client to object to specific investment as long as objection relates to that level of decision making
- If it does not, it is **important to withdraw recommendation** and move back to more general level of decision making that involves source of objection
- Resolution may require **modification of either broad portfolio balance decision** or **asset allocation strategy**, which in turn will necessitate redesigned target portfolio

## Obtaining Cash from the Portfolio for the Client's Expenditures

### Client Need for Income vs. Total Return

**Advisor:** "Here is the recommended target portfolio. It is broadly diversified among multiple asset classes and will maximize the portfolio's expected return subject to your volatility tolerance and time horizon."

**Client:** "Nice portfolio, but I couldn't possibly live on that yield. Why don't we cut down on the stock investments and reposition the proceeds in bonds until the portfolio yield matches my income needs?"

**Table 13-1** shows components of return for **three asset mixes** of bonds and stocks

**Assumptions:**

- Particular client should have **asset mix of 50 percent bonds and 50 percent stocks**, given her investment time horizon and volatility tolerance
- This portfolio has **expected total return of 9 percent**, composed of:
  - **4 percent current yield** plus
  - **5 percent average rate of capital appreciation**
- If client has **$1 million portfolio**, this mix will generate **income yield of $40,000**

**But what if she needs $60,000 per year to live on?**

- This would require **invasion of principal**
- Most clients have had it drilled into them to **"never spend your principal"**
- Although this is well-intentioned advice in spirit, **too literal an interpretation** of warning can result in poor investment decisions

### The Danger of Over-Emphasis on Income Yield

**Properly balanced portfolio maximizes total return** for client subject to his or her volatility tolerance

- If income yield on portfolio is **less than what is needed for current expenditures**, **the client's first impulse is often to boost portfolio yield** by selling appreciation-oriented equity investments in order to buy more interest-generating investments
- In our example, **client would have to move to a portfolio composed entirely of bonds** in order to generate current income yield sufficient for her needs

**Ironically, if client does this**, she will subject herself to two dangers she is trying to avoid by not spending her principal:

1. **Action to increase her income yield from 4 percent to 6 percent will be accompanied by a 3 percent reduction in total return**, thereby **increasing her exposure to purchasing power erosion**!

### The Total Return Framework Solution

**The solution is to educate client to think in terms of total return** (yield plus capital appreciation) rather than income yield

- Within total return framework, **clients gain an appreciation** that it is **better to spend a little principal to supplement lower income** that results from portfolio with higher total return
- **Than to choose portfolio with higher income yield but lower total return**

### TABLE 13-1: Components of Return

| | Asset Mix 1 | Asset Mix 2 | Asset Mix 3 |
|---|---|---|---|
| Bonds | 100% | 50% | 0% |
| Stocks | 0% | 50% | 100% |
| Total | 100% | 100% | 100% |
| Asset mix yield | 6% | 4% | 2% |
| Capital appreciation | 0 | 5% | 10% |
| Asset mix total return | 6% | 9% | 12% |

## Sustainable Portfolio Withdrawal Rates

**In Chapter 2** we discussed plight of **50-year old widow with $1 million** invested in certificates of deposit

- In world of even **modest levels of persistent inflation**, purchasing power of portfolio can **erode significantly over time** if too much of its average total return is used to meet expenditures

**Some clients respond** by saying they do not want to leave huge portfolio to survivors, and so **periodic invasions of principal are acceptable to them**

**The problem with this:**

- Even an **intentional full liquidation of principal may not materially increase cash available** for meeting expenditures

**Example:**

- Widow with **$1 million invested in certificates of deposit at 5 percent** has **interest income of $50,000 per year**
- If instead of spending only interest she systematically liquidates principal over her **30-year life expectancy**, her annual cash flow will increase only to approximately **$65,000**
- This is of **little help in an inflationary environment** that will more than triple cost of living over her remaining life expectancy

### Maintaining Purchasing Power Through Withdrawal Rate

**Ideally, it would be advisable to maintain purchasing power** of investment portfolio by **limiting portfolio withdrawals** to rate equal to **difference between average total expected return and average inflation rate**

**Table 13-2** shows **sustainable real portfolio withdrawal rates** for three asset mixes of bonds and stocks previously discussed

### TABLE 13-2: Sustainable Real Portfolio Withdrawal Rates

| | Asset Mix 1 | Asset Mix 2 | Asset Mix 3 |
|---|---|---|---|
| Bonds | 100% | 50% | 0% |
| Stocks | 0% | 50% | 100% |
| Total | 100% | 100% | 100% |
| Asset mix total return | 6% | 9% | 12% |
| (Inflation adjustment) | (4) | (4) | (4) |
| Withdrawal rate | 2% | 5% | 8% |
<!-- pp. 321-340 -->

## Resolving Problems Encountered During Implementation (continued from p. 301)

### Portfolio Withdrawals and Inflation Protection

- **Cash withdrawal rates** are modest relative to portfolio size but have one important characteristic: as the portfolio maintains purchasing power by growing at a rate sufficient to offset inflation, the cash withdrawals from the portfolio can also be increased over time to keep pace with inflation
- In practice, many clients will be unable to limit their withdrawals to the level necessary to maintain portfolio purchasing power
- But even a small portion of the total return left untouched to partially offset inflation will **enhance the client's long-term financial security**

## Conclusion

> "That's enough, Charlie. Don't show me any more figures; I've got the smell of the thing now."
> — **Henry Ford (1863-1947)** to Charles Sorenson, his lieutenant

> "Certainty generally is illusion, and repose is not the destiny of man."
> — **Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr. (1841-1935)**, The Path of the Law

> "The greatest gift is the power to estimate correctly the value of things."
> — **Francois, Duc de La Rochefoucauld (1613-1680)**, Maximes, 1664

### The Simplicity and Difficulty of Money Management

- **Money management is simple but not easy**
- It is simple because the principles of successful investing are relatively few in number and are easy to understand
- Although all clients face a variety of risks in the management of their money, the two most important are **inflation** and **volatility of returns**
- To the extent which a portfolio is structured to avoid one of these risks, it unfortunately becomes exposed to the other
- For this reason, **clients must determine which risk is more dangerous to them**
- **Time horizon is the relevant dimension** along which this judgment is made

### Time Horizon and Risk Trade-offs

- For **short time horizons**, volatility is a bigger risk than inflation, and such portfolios should accordingly follow an asset allocation strategy that gives greater weight to **interest-generating investments with stable principal values**
- For **long time horizons**, inflation is the more significant danger, and these portfolios should therefore have **larger allocations to equity investments**
- Regardless of the time horizon, however, the **risk-mitigation benefits of broad diversification** argue for the utilization of multiple asset classes for all clients regardless of volatility tolerance

### Client Education and Involvement

- Because money management is simple, it is **within the capacity of all clients to be meaningfully involved** with the investment decision-making process
- It is neither necessary nor advisable for a client to leave major investment decisions to the sole discretion of the investment advisor
- It is the client's money, and he or she will have to live with the results
- As a client becomes **better educated** regarding the money management process, his or her volatility tolerance will change toward that which is most appropriate given the facts of the situation
- With greater understanding, **better decisions will be made** and the client will also benefit by having a **realistic frame of reference for evaluating the results**
- This leads to **greater equanimity and staying power**, both of which are extremely important to the realization of investment objectives

### Dealing with Uncertainty

- Although money management is simple, **it is not easy**
- There are **uncertainties inherent in the money management process** that cannot be avoided, and these uncertainties are hard for clients to live with
- It is natural to fear the unknown and want to reduce or eliminate uncertainty whenever possible
- Past anecdote from **Federal Reserve Chairman Paul A. Volcker** at an Institute of Chartered Financial Analysts' conference: **"You cannot hedge the world"**
- **Mount Fuji story**: Toured Japan many years ago. Several people in the group wanted to see majestic Mount Fuji, and so a day trip by bus was organized. They were warned before they left there was probably no better than a 50/50 chance of actually seeing the mountain peak due to poor visibility conditions typical during that time of year
- When they arrived at Mount Fuji, it was nowhere in sight. Heavy fog and clouds blanketed the entire valley and mountain range
- Having invested four hours by bus to get there, several people wanted to take pictures anyway. Despite how carefully they focused their cameras, however, the fog would not go away
- All they could do was get a sharper picture of the fog
- **So it is with money management**. Clients often believe that as professional advisors, we should have some method to eliminate the uncertainties that are so difficult for them to live with
- As we focus on the uncertainties inherent in money management, however, **all we can hope to accomplish is to get a better picture of the uncertainties—we cannot eliminate them**
- As a friend of the author who is an economist once said: **"The window to the future is opaque"**

### Uncertainty and Long-Term Perspective

- As difficult as it is to live with, **uncertainty is not necessarily bad**
- For the client with a long time horizon, volatility is rewarded by the higher expected returns of equity investing
- If we can teach our clients to understand this, they can use it to their advantage
- There is a difference, though, between **intellectually understanding something** and living with it on a day-to-day basis
- **Successful investing therefore will always be as much of a psychological process as it is a money management endeavor**

### The Importance of Long-term Commitment

- Money management is not easy, because without a **very firm commitment to long-term investment policies** within an asset allocation framework, it is easy for clients to be distracted by investment schemes that promise high returns with little or no risk
- Those who depart from long-term strategy in order to pursue these investments end up with in the end of the day portfolios in the same way they collect shells at the beach, **picking up whatever catches their eye at the moment**
- This bottom line is that there is nothing safe, quick, and easy way to build wealth
- As an old saying reminds us: **"If wishes were horses, beggars would ride"**

### The Las Vegas Casino Analogy

- Imagine that you are standing in the middle of a large group of slot machines at a Las Vegas casino
- All around you, you can hear the sound of people winning as the jackpots from lucky pulls of the handle drop coins noisily into metal trays
- Although it is always true that at any point in time there are those who are ahead of the game (and these people always stand out from the crowd), on average the **flow of money is from the pockets of those who play the game to the casino that owns the machines**
- Objectively we know this, but **in the midst of the magic of a casino, our excitement can override better judgment** as we win just often enough to make us believe that we can get ahead by continuing to play
- Fueling our hope for beating this system is the evidence of our senses, which tells us that other people are indeed winning—**if only we can find a "hot" slot machine**

### Day-to-Day Investment Environment Distractions

- The messages our clients receive from the day-to-day investment environment can be as **distracting and misleading** as the sounds of intermittently winning slot machines
- Whether it be a new **market-timing guru** or an **investment idea** that seems to promise better results than a well-diversified portfolio, there will always be **temptations** that encourage clients to depart from a well-conceived, long-term strategy
- At times, adherence to long-term asset allocation decisions can seem dangerous, as we urge our clients during **bear markets** to allocate more money to common stocks in order to restore the proper balance in their portfolios
- At other times, the equity commitment may become too great as a result of a **bull market surge**. To persuade clients to rebalance their portfolios back to target asset allocations in the midst of a bull market can sound like a parent telling a child that he has to leave a party **just when everybody really starts to have fun**
- These difficulties are another reason why money management is not easy

### Historical Role of Money Managers

- Historically, the money manager's job has been to **enhance return and minimize risk** by exercising superior skill in **security selection and/or market timing**
- Success has been measured in terms of whether the manager has **"beaten the market"**
- The engine driving portfolio performance was presumed to be the superior talent of the manager
- Little attention was paid to the **asset allocation decisions**

### Modern Efficient Markets and Asset Allocation Focus

- Today, the **capital markets are highly efficient** and it is dangerous to presume that superior skill can be safely relied on as the primary determinant of a portfolio's performance
- If future performance results will be determined primarily by the **asset allocation decisions** made in the management of the portfolio, it should be at the **asset allocation level of decision making** that investment advisors and their clients address issues of risk and return
- This implies that **client assessment of portfolio design and performance expectations should be based primarily on the risk/return characteristics of the capital markets themselves** rather than on the elusive positive/negatives of active management
- We would do well to follow the advice of **R. Buckminster Fuller**, creator of the Geodesic Dome, who said: **"Use forces; don't fight them"**

### Implications for Investment Advisory Profession

- If money management is simple but not easy, what are the implications of this for the investment advisory profession?
- Because it is simple, **advisors have a tremendous opportunity to add value for clients by properly educating them**
- **Knowledgeable clients** will more likely choose and remain committed to those strategies that are most appropriate for realizing their objectives
- In addition to being **educators**, we must also be **architects** and **general contractors**, designing and implementing **broadly diversified investment strategies** that we create in collaboration with our clients
- Because money management is not easy, we will have important work to do on an ongoing basis
- As the capital markets move, our services will be needed to **provide perspective** to our clients regarding their investment experience
- Particularly during **extreme market conditions**, clients may need the **discipline and assurance of a steady hand** that urges them to remain committed to their long-term strategies
- We have witnessed many changes in the world capital markets over the past several decades
- More changes will undoubtedly occur in the future

### Client Needs in Evolving Investment Environment

- In this evolving investment environment, clients do not need **sporadic investment suggestions**
- They need and will value the **comprehensive management of their portfolios** by **knowledgeable investment professionals** committed to their financial well-being

